#Text=Mummy Juanita
#Text=Momia Juanita

#Text=( Spanish for " Mummy Juanita " ) , also known as the Lady of Ampato , is the well-preserved frozen body of an Inca girl [ 1 ] who was killed as an offering to the Inca gods sometime between 1450 and 1480 when she was approximately 12 – 15 years old .

column1: #Text=She was discovered on Mount Ampato ( part of the Andes cordillera ) in southern Peru in 1995 by anthropologist Johan Reinhard and his Peruvian climbing partner , Miguel Zárate .

#Text=" Juanita " has been on display in the Catholic University of Santa María ' s Museum of Andean Sanctuaries ( Museo Santuarios Andinos ) in Arequipa , Peru , almost continuously since 1996 , and was displayed on a tour of Japan in 1999 .
#Text=In 1995 , Time magazine chose her as one of the world 's top ten discoveries .
#Text=Between May and June 1996 , she was exhibited in the headquarters of the National Geographic Society in Washington , D.C. , in a specially acclimatized conservation display unit .
#Text=In its June 1996 issue , National Geographic included an article dedicated to the discovery of Juanita . [ 2 ]
#Text=Discovery
#Text=In September 1995 , during an ascent of Mt . Ampato ( 20,700ft , 6309 m ) , Johan Reinhard and Zárate found in the crater a bundle that had fallen from an Inca site on the summit .
#Text=To their astonishment , the bundle turned out to contain the frozen body of a young girl .
#Text=They also found many items that had been left as offerings to the Inca gods .
#Text=The items were strewn about the mountain slope , down which the body had fallen .
#Text=These included statues and food items .
#Text=The body and the items were transported to Arequipa , where the body was initially kept in a special refrigerator at the Catholic University . [ 3 ]

#Text=Two more ice mummies , a young girl and a boy , were discovered in an archaeological expedition led by Dr. Reinhard and Prof. Jose Antonio Chavez in October 1995 , and they recovered another female mummy on Ampato in December 1997 .
#Text=Owing to melting caused by volcanic ash from the nearby erupting volcano of Sabancaya , most of the Inca burial site had collapsed down into a gully that led into the crater .
#Text=Reinhard published a detailed account of the discovery in his 2006 book entitled , The Ice Maiden : Inca Mummies , Mountain Gods , and Sacred Sites in the Andes .
#Text=Scientific analyses
#Text=Body

#Text=As Reinhard and Zárate struggled on Ampato 's summit to lift the heavy bundle containing Juanita 's body , they realized that her body mass had probably been increased by freezing of the flesh .
#Text=When initially weighed in Arequipa , the bundle containing " Juanita " weighed over 90 pounds ( 40.82 kilos ) .
#Text=Their realization turned out to be correct ; Juanita is almost entirely frozen , making her a substantial scientific find .
#Text=Like only a few other high-altitude Inca mummies , Juanita was found frozen and thus her remains and garments were not desiccated like those of mummies found in other parts of the world .
#Text=She was naturally mummified , instead of being artificially mummified , as is the case with Egyptian mummies .

#Text=Her skin , organs , tissues , blood , hair , stomach contents , and garments are extremely well-preserved , offering scientists a rare glimpse into Inca culture during the reign of the Sapa Inca Pachacuti ( reigned 1438 – 1471/1472 ) .
#Text=Analysis of her stomach contents revealed that she ate a meal of vegetables , six to eight hours before her death . [ 4 ]
#Text=Clothing and adornments
#Text=Juanita was wrapped in a brightly coloured burial tapestry ( or " aksu " ) .
#Text=Her head was adorned with a cap made from the feathers of a red macaw , and she wore a lively woollen alpaca shawl fastened with a silver clasp .
#Text=She was fully clothed in garments resembling the finest textiles from the Inca capital city of Cusco .
#Text=This , in addition to evidence of excellent health , suggests that she may have come from a noble Cuzco family .
#Text=These accoutrements were almost perfectly preserved , providing valuable insight into sacred Inca textiles and on how the Inca nobility dressed .
#Text=Tools and equipment
#Text=Found with her in the burial tapestry was a collection of grave goods : bowls , pins , and figurines made of gold , silver , and shell .
#Text=Genetic analysis

#Text=According to the Institute for Genomic Research ( TIGR ) , the closest kin they could find in the database in 1996 were the Ngobe people of Panama , but the later research has shown her to share genetic patterns found in people from the Andes .

#Text=Scientists at TIGR examined two mitochondrial DNA D loop sequences and found that Hypervariable region 1 ( HV1 ) was consistent with mitochondrial haplogroup A2 , one of the four Native American gene groups .
#Text=Hypervariable region 2 ( HV2 ) included a unique sequence not found in any of the current mitochondrial DNA databases . [ 5 ]
#Text=Her haplotype is 16111T , 16223T , 16290T , 16319A . [ 6 ]

#Text=In accordance with the genetic world map and genetic patterns , her HV2 DNA sequence was also related with the ancient races originally from Taiwan and Korea , which supports the theory that Paleo-Indians had Pacific links . [ 7 ] [ 8 ] [ 9 ]
#Text=Cause of death
#Text=Radiologist Elliot Fishman concluded that she was killed by blunt trauma to the head .
#Text=He observed that her cracked right eye socket and the two-inch fracture in her skull are injuries " typical of someone who has been hit by a baseball bat .
